µJEThe scene in its present state is divided into the high-tech end on the PC-Windows side and the many lower-tech scenes like Amiga, C64, GBA, Playstation and so on. Every platform has its own style, culture and attitude as people with specific preferences are drawn to specific hardware. This is natural behaviour and nothing to complain about, but the problem is that the borders are mostly closed between the platforms. This has two consequences, stagnation and extinction.

Stagnation is when all demos begin to look the same as most people on that platform think the same way and no new influences can cross the borders. Extinction is when people leave a scene because they see an either-or situation, will you stick with Amiga or move on to PC if you have to choose?

Here comes my point: Multiplatform demomaking is about not having to choose a platform. All demos can be watched on (almost) all machines, you can stick with whatever machine you like most and still be part of the whole, of the global scene. You might hold on to the culture and society of your platform, but you might exchange impressions with people you else never would have reached. Imagine discussing your favourite demos on IRC with some guy and finding out he is a Mac scener! He might have a background in illustration business and he might join your group as graphician. This is exactly what I pointed at in my previous article µC3µA0010"Hacking is dead - Long live art!"µC4, being part of a global art-centered creative scene attracts me more than squeezing some more frames per second from my particular machine.

The rest of this article has a more practical approach. This is a comparing review of methods to release demos on multiple platforms and is primarily directed to coders.

